The President has declared a national emergency to address the threat of terrorism to the United States, particularly in response to the attacks on September 11, 2001. On September 9, 2019, the President signed an Executive Order to strengthen and consolidate sanctions against international terrorism and further address the national emergency. The President has determined that the threat of terrorism continues to pose an unusual and extraordinary threat to national security, foreign policy, and the economy. Therefore, the national emergency declared in 2001, as well as the measures adopted to address it, will continue beyond September 23, 2022. This decision is in accordance with the National Emergencies Act.